Title: Globally Convergent Algorithms for Maximum a Posteriori Transmission Tomography  
Author: Kenneth Lange and Jeffrey A. Fessler 
Keyword: Key words: maximum likelihood, smoothing prior, EM algorithm, convergence  
Address: Ann Arbor, MI 48109-2029  Ann Arbor, MI 48109-0552  
Affiliation: Department of Biostatistics, School of Public Health 1 University of Michigan  Bldg.  
Note: IEEE TRANSACTIONS ON IMAGE PROCESSING: TO APPEAR 1  Division of Nuclear Medicine, Department of Internal Medicine 2 3840 Kresge III  
Email: Email klange@umich.edu  Email fessler@umich.edu  
Phone: Phone: 313-936-3287, FAX: 313-763-2215  
Abstract: This paper reviews and compares three maximum likelihood algorithms for transmission tomography. One of these algorithms is the EM algorithm, one is based on a convexity argument devised by De Pierro in the context of emission tomography, and one is an ad hoc gradient algorithm. The algorithms enjoy desirable local and global convergence properties and combine gracefully with Bayesian smoothing priors. Preliminary numerical testing of the algorithms on simulated data suggest that the convex algorithm and the ad hoc gradient algorithm are compu-tationally superior to the EM algorithm. This superiority stems from the larger number of exponentiations required by the EM algorithm. The convex and gradient algorithms are well adapted to parallel computing. 
